[1]
Date: 4 Aug 2003
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: The Palm Beach Post (West Palm Beach) 3 Aug 2003 [accessed 4 Aug
2003; edited]
<http://www.palmbeachpost.com/accent/content/auto/epaper/editions/today/accent_f3a28cb744c631560022.html>

Local transmission of _P.vivax_ malaria suspected in Florida
--------------------------------------------------
Worldwide, malaria is probably the worst disease a mosquito can inflict on
a human being, but malaria is extraordinarily rare in Florida. There were 2
cases in Palm Beach County reported recently, and 2 more in 1996, also here.
The recent pair of cases in Lake Worth have touched off a massive local
campaign of spraying and warnings to local people, to stay indoors at dawn
and dusk, use DEET-based mosquito repellent if they must venture outside,
and remove any standing water on their property. Some 35 000 households in
a 9-square-mile area will be alerted to beware of mosquitoes.
The warnings have as much to do with panic control as mosquito control, but
they are vivid proof of how serious an illness malaria is.
The 2 recent cases are probably _Plasmodium vivax_ and most likely came
from a mosquito that bit someone coming here from outside the U.S., then
transmitted the parasite. There is no cause for panic, said Gary Goode, a
technician with the Palm Beach County Mosquito Control District.
"That mosquito was probably an _Anopheles quadrimaculatus_. If so, we're
lucky, it's probably dead by now," Goode said. "Mosquitoes don't live
forever. They burn out."
Yellow fever, once the scourge of Florida and the Caribbean, is extremely
deadly but is all but unknown in the U.S. today. Dengue fever, which is
also carried by mosquitoes, can be mild on first attack, but a second
attack can be fatal.
In Florida, the greatest dangers posed by mosquitoes come from 3 viruses:
West Nile, Eastern equine encephalitis, and St. Louis encephalitis. The
fatality rates for Eastern equine encephalitis are 50 to 70 percent,
according to Jonathan F. Day, a medical entomologist at the University of
Florida's Vero Beach laboratory. Therefore EEE, as it is known by its
acronym, probably poses the greatest danger to Floridians, though so far it
is more prevalent in north and central Florida than South Florida.
The fatality rates for West Nile virus and St. Louis encephalitis are much
lower, around 10 percent.
