[2]
Date: 4 Aug 2003
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: The Post and Courier (Charleston) 29 Jul 2003 [accessed 4 Aug 2003]
[edited]
<http://www.charleston.net/stories/072903/wor_29malaria.shtml>

Florida seeks person first infected by malaria
----------------------------------
Health officials knocked on doors Monday seeking a person who they believe
contracted malaria on a trip abroad and passed it via mosquitoes to 2
neighbors.
The 2 men who live 4 houses apart were hospitalized briefly and are
recovering from relatively mild cases of malaria. No other cases of the
disease have been confirmed, and investigators said residents shouldn't be
alarmed.
Still, health workers alerted neighborhood residents to the possible risk
of malaria infection, and mosquito control workers stepped up aerial
spraying and placement in the area.
Health officials were combing the neighborhood trying to find the source of
the malaria, which is rare in the United States but is common in Asia,
Africa, Central and South America, the Mediterranean countries, and islands
in the Pacific and Caribbean. Neither man had traveled to a high-risk area.
"It's not something to be overly concerned about. ... In terms of it
spreading, it's extremely unlikely," said Louise Causer, a medical
epidemiologist with the federal Centers for Disease Control and Prevention.
The agency was helping the local and state health departments in the case.
Most of the 1200 cases of malaria diagnosed in the United States each year
involve people who have traveled to infected areas, Causer said. People can
contract the disease also through tainted blood transfusions, intravenous
needles, and unsanitary tattoo equipment.
The disease can cause headaches, nausea, vomiting, and other symptoms. It
can be fatal if left untreated.
Palm Beach County Health Department Director Dr. Jean Malecki said it was
possible that other mosquitoes had bitten the original infected person and
were carrying the malaria parasite, but that officials were hoping
increased spraying would kill any mosquitoes that might potentially spread it.
Previous cases in Palm Beach County were in 1996, when 2 men were infected.
The cause of their infection was never discovered.
Malecki said the second occurrence of malaria in the same place was likely
simply a matter of chance. State Health Secretary Dr. John Agwunobi added
that people may tend to travel overseas from Palm Beach County more often
than some other counties.
Florida residents already have been warned to take precautions against
mosquito bites to protect against West Nile virus and encephalitis.
Agwunobi recommended wearing long pants and sleeves at dusk and dawn when
mosquitoes feed, using repellant, and removing standing water from yards.
--
